author: @xmark2
text: I installed python2 first and after python3 but python3 didn't want to run. I also used "#! python3" but it didn't want to run my codes as python3, and the path is in the environment variable, so it should work, but didn't .  Solution that I found: - navigate to python27 directory and create a bat file with the following content:  cmd /k "c:\python27\python.exe" %*  -save as "python2.bat" -stay in the same python27 directory and create another bat file for python36 with the following content:  cmd /k "c:\python36\python.exe" %*  -save as "python3.bat" and after if I open command prompt: - if I type "python - -version" => 2.7 as default -if "python2 - -version" => 2.7 as runs the code -if "python3 - -version" => 3.6 as runs the code  I hope this helps if someone has similar issue that I had today.:)

author: @shanedetsch
text: You can also use `pyenv`; on a mac you can do:  (1) brew install pyenv NOTE: How to install brew http://brew.sh/   (2) Add the below to ~/.bash_profile export PYENV_ROOT=/usr/local/opt/pyenv   eval "$(pyenv init -)" export PATH=$PATH:$PYENV_ROOT/bin:$PYENV_ROOT/shims  (3) Run `source ~/.bash_profile` to refresh your .bash_profile  (4) Check what versions of python you can install with pyenv by running `pyenv versions`  I have 2.7.10 and 3.5.0 so I will install these pyenv install 3.5.0 && pyenv install 2.7.10 && pyenv rehash && source ~/.bash_profile  ( NOTE: you may not have $PYENV_ROOT/shims until after you run your first `pyenv install <version>` command )  (5) Now switch versions  by running either `pyenv local 2.7.10` or `pyenv local 3.5.0`  Example:  $ which python /usr/local/opt/pyenv/shims/python $ pyenv local 2.7.10 $ python --version Python 2.7.10 $ pyenv local 3.5.0 $ python --version Python 3.5.0
